<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Andreatta Blames Financiers for Impeding Privatizations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1403160194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1721 GMT 12 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1403160194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Andreatta Blames High Finance for </F>
Privatisation Hold-Ups"] 
  [Text] Bologna, 12 Mar (ANSA) -- High finance has been 
instrumental in holding up Italy's ambitious but slow-moving 
privatisation process, Foreign Minister Beniamino Andreatta, a 
respected economist, said Saturday [12 March]. 
  At a meeting of European business managers here, the foreign 
minister said "for the past twelve months I have been asking for 
consultants to be named to get the privatisations of STET [Turin 
Telephone Finance Company], ENEL [National Electric Power Board] 
and the petrol sector off the ground." 
  "Well," said Andreatta, who served as budget minister in the 
government of Giuliano Amato which gave a push to the 
privatisation process, "these nominations have been frozen for 
twelve months, in a subtle game in which the great potentates of 
high finance have played their part." 
  "I am not claiming," he went on, "that there is some kind of 
feud between some politicians and high finance. Personally I am 
convinced that we need to keep checks on the influence of high 
finance.... In the past few months I have seen thousands of 
objections raised by high finance to a process that must be done 
well, following the example set in Britain and France." 
  The foreign minister voiced worries that some areas of large 
industry are suggesting that partnerships should be limited to 
those with industry in France. "But I do not think that deals 
between two countries with rather interventionist tendencies 
would be the best thing for our privatisation process." 
  The possibility of the privatisation process being wound 
down 
by the winners of the March 27-28 general elections was played 
down by Andreatta who forecast a governing alliance which 
differed considerably from the coalitions as they head into the 
vote. 
  "And in this reorganisation, I think that intermediate force 
will prevail in the left-wing, right-wing and centrist line-ups, 
allowing a continuation with the action set in motion by the 
Amato government and (the current) government of (Carlo Azeglio) 
Ciampi, privatisations included," he said. 

</TEXT>

