<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Draft Austerity Finance Bill Sets Out Strict Criteria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1503154594 Milan CORRIERE DELLA SERA in Italian 15 Mar 94 
p 20--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1503154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Milan CORRIERE DELLA SERA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Dino Vaiano: "The Second Republic Is Born With </F>
an Austerity Finance Bill -- Ministers on a Strict Diet"] 
  [Text] Rome -- The Second Republic's finance bill is taking 
its first steps. With a strict diet for ministers who, next 
year, must keep their budgets riveted to 1994 levels. Entities 
such as the Post Office and the Railways will be able to cover 
"further demands" only through price and tariff increases. The 
basic objective is to ensure a stable relationship between 
public indebtedness and GDP until 1995. The outlines of the 
next three years' austerity program are contained in a circular 
which has just been completed by the Treasury Minister, setting 
out strict criteria for preparing budget forecasts for 1994 and 
for the 1995-97 three-year period. The document issued by the 
State Audit Office also anticipates certain alarming figures 
with regard to this year's government accounts: "The latest 
development of the main indicators leads us to believe that it 
will not be easy to achieve the forecasts of economic growth 
previously formulated for the present year. 
  ``The reduction in the average rate of inflation from the 
4.2 
percent achieved in 1993 to the 3.5 percent figure programmed 
for 1994 could prove problematic. Problems are also possible 
relating to the impact on domestic prices of the monetary 
devaluation. The recent impressive fall in interest rates could 
well flatten out and even come to a halt.'' 
  It will be up to the quarterly cash report to set out, in 
the 
coming weeks, the official government forecasts on public 
finances. It is unlikely to depart substantially from the figure 
of a 15 trillion lira deficit put forward by the Monetary Fund, 
which has scaled down the growth of our economy to a rate of 1.1 
percent. The Treasury warns: "The restrictive approach taken 
in recent years to budget forecasts must be maintained." There 
are no short cuts. The Audit Office indicates as a reference 
point the objectives set out in the monitoring procedure agreed 
to with the European Union. Under attack are the acquisition of 
goods and services, investments, and transfers to decentralized 
entities. The watchword for the next maneuver will be "nominal 
nonvariance." Expenditure on goods and services may not be 
higher than those of 1994, and with an expansion of no more than 
2 percent in 1996 and 1.5 percent in 1997. The Audit Office is 
assuming that a hatchet will be taken to amounts earmarked for 
studies, inquiries, reports, committees, commissions, special 
assignments, and publicity, in order to "arrive at their 
elimination or at least to a significant scaling down." The 
strictures will also apply to defense: "It is necessary to 
proceed to redefine the various plans and projects, taking 
account of the changing international context and the coming 
into operation of the new defense model, with a concomitant 
postponement of expenditures for modernization and development, 
compatible with the implementation of the new programs." 
  But ministers' slimming cure will not be enough. The next 
finance bill will also have to "freeze," for three years, at 
1994 levels, the special funds for new legislative provisions. 
On its last page the circular fixes the broad lines for the 
three-year maneuver: For tax income one can assume a nominal 
GDP growth on the order of 4.5 to 5.0 percent in 1995 and 4.0 to 
4.5 percent in 1996 and 1997. Current 1995 expenses will have 
to be contained within the levels set by the 1994 adjusted 
budget, while expenditure on personnel and the acquisition of 
goods and services essential for the operation of government may 
not grow by more than 2.0 percent in 1996 and 1.5 percent in 
1997. Investments over the three-year period may not grow by 
more than 2.5 percent, 2.0 percent and 1.5 percent respectively. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

