<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ulster Unionist Delegation To Visit U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503164094 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1630 GMT 15 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1503164094 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Deric Henderson, PRESS ASSOCIATION] </F>
  [Text] A party of Ulster Unionists is to visit America next 
month for talks with State Department officials and politicians. 
  Party leader James Molyneaux is heading a delegation which 
will visit New York and Washington. 
  The party said there was a particular need to counter 
attempts by the republican support group Noraid and other 
elements to undermine business and industrial interest in 
Northern Ireland. 
  A statement from the party said a series of routine visits 
by 
senior party members had helped to "offset the problems being 
caused by a small but vociferous minority within the 
Irish-American community." 
  Fermanagh-South Tyrone MP Mr Ken Maginnis, Euro MP Mr Jim 
Nicholson and party secretary Jeffrey Donaldson leave with Mr 
Molyneaux on April 16. 
  Last month Mr Molyneaux refused to accept an invitation to 
address a New York conference attended by the Sinn Fein 
president Gerry Adams. 
  The party statement added: "Mr Molyneaux believes this is an 
appropriate time to reinforce relationships on a broader front 
and has been encouraged by the number of invitations to 
undertake a more formal visit at this time." 

</TEXT>

