<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Commentary </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1503135094 Berlin DIE WELT in German 15 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1503135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Carl Gustav Stroehm commentary: "Hope for Bosnia"] </F>
  [Text] Under U.S. aegis the Bosnian Muslims and the 
Bosnian Croats have made a breakthrough: A constitution for a 
federation in Bosnia seems to have been set down. The country 
will be formed of cantons with Muslim and Croatian majorities 
respectively. The office of the head of state is to alternate 
annually between a Muslim and a Croat. 
  However, the problem lies in the details: Everything now 
depends on whether the Muslims and the Croats really do 
cooperate -- or whether the former are just waiting to 
outmaneuver the latter, and the latter, for their part, see the 
Bosnian solution just as an interim step toward joining the 
Republic of Croatia. 
  The biggest factor of uncertainty are the Serbs. The U.S. 
hopes that the Serbs will participate in the Bosnian federation. 
However, there is the danger that including them might blow up 
the building. The Serbs do not want Bosnia -- they want a 
Greater Serbia. 
  If the bilateral Muslim-Croat federation comes about, then 
something like a new Yalta line will be drawn between the Serbs 
on the one hand and the Muslims and Croats on the other. 
Whatever is on the western side of the line is influenced by 
NATO and the European Union. Whatever is to the east of it -- 
that is, Serbia and the territories conquered by the Serbs -- 
will be under Russian protection. 
  The Croats and the Muslims derive one satisfaction from all 
this: This time they are on the "western side." The first World 
Bank loan of $700 million has already been prepared for Croatia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

