<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minimum Fish Prices Extended in Defiance of EU </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603105694 Paris AFP in English 1043 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1603105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 16 (AFP) -- Minimum prices for imports 
of seven species of fish are to be extended by two months, the 
French Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries said Wednesday [16 
March], one day after the European Union ruled out such a move. 
  In a statement, the ministry said the decision had been 
taken 
overnight after strong lobbying by France. 
  "The (EU) Commission in Brussels will this morning ratify 
the 
political accord reached overnight which will extend for two 
months the arrangements put in place at France's request." 
  "The French Government intervened vigorously to demand that 
the Commission review its decision to suspend the system of 
minimum import prices," the statement said, quoting Agriculture 
and Fisheries Minister Jean Puech. 
  On Tuesday in Brussels, a spokesman for the European 
Commission, the EU's executive arm, said the system would not be 
extended as there were no data showing that the market is 
destabilized at present by cheap fish imports. 
  The spokesman added however that if such data were 
forthcoming, the commission "is prepared to re-establish the 
minimum prices." 
  The prices had been decided on last February 4 and expire 
March 15. They are aimed at protecting EU fishermen against 
excessively cheap imports. Minimum import prices had been set 
for fish last year as well, from February to December. 
  France asked the commission to extend the minimum prices 
last 
week. French fishermen have staged demonstrations, sometimes 
violent, to protest against low-cost imports from non-EU 
countries that drive down prices of French fish. 
  The ministry added in its statement Wednesday that: "Our 
firmness has paid off. The European Union now has two months to 
take a serious look at the difficulties in the fishing sector." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-19340 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu051_i_94005" </HT>


