<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Defends Youth Training Contract </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1503131994 Paris LA TRIBUNE DESFOSSES in French 15 Mar 94 
p 6 </F>

<F P=103> BR1503131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LA TRIBUNE DESFOSSES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] After the demonstrations against the youth 
vocational training contract (CIP), Budget Minister Nicolas 
Sarkozy declared: "We will maintain the CIP. This is the 
question that I would like to ask to all demonstrators." He 
added, "Should we tolerate that 750,000 young people are 
unemployed, or should we do something about it?" He insisted 
that "we have to solve this problem, and we will solve it," 
adding "the question is not so much whether we stick to the CIP; 
the question is: what is the formula to give jobs to 
youngsters." Nicolas Sarkozy continued: "We suggest this 
formula; nobody is suggesting another one. If it produces 
results, if it reduces youth unemployment, we will have done 
something useful for France." According to the minister, "all 
traditional measures have failed." And he asked: "Why do you 
want us to stop this experiment for electoral reasons? And what 
if the French think it better to experiment than to fail?" 

</TEXT>

