<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   ESA Orders Equipment Worth 50 Million Markkas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503205794 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1700 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1503205794 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The European Space Agency, ESA, has ordered 
equipment, programs, and design work worth over FMk [Finnish 
markkas] 50 million from Finland for the Envisat 1 satellite 
that studies the environment and that will be launched in 1998. 
This is the biggest ever order for Finland in the space sector. 
The order will employ several dozen people in Finland's top 
technology enterprises until 1998. 
  The orders from Finland concentrate on Envisat's GOMOS 
[Global Ozone Monitoring by Occultation of Stars] instrument 
that measures the ozone layer. Finland has been taking part in 
developing the GOMOS instrument from the beginning, Kari Tilli, 
the technical director of the Technology Development Center, 
said today. 

</TEXT>

