<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Disturbed' Relations Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703112094 Berlin DIE WELT in German 17 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1703112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Bernt Conrad: "Disturbed Relationship"] </F>
  [Text] The formerly smooth Franco-German cooperation has 
been disturbed. Bonn's irritation at the fact that Helmut Kohl 
has not been invited to the victory celebrations in Normandy and 
ill-feelings in Paris regarding the fact that the allied troops 
in Berlin will be sent off without a parade, are symptoms of 
disrupted communication. 
  This is particularly disadvantageous in view of the latent 
insecurity about the new role of the united Germany that can be 
felt among our Western neighbors. Will Germany's regained 
central position change anything about the Western orientation 
in our foreign policy, particularly about the Franco-German 
friendship as the European axis? 
  One ought to discuss these things openly with our neighbors 
on the Seine. Yet, despite the general assertions by the 
federal chancellor, this is obviously virtually not being done. 
  Yet, as one expert on French politics stated, the 
Franco-German friendship is not a natural river, the course of 
which can be neglected. It has to be cultivated. 
  The extension of the European Union [EU] toward the east, 
the 
position toward Russia, containment of the conflict in the 
Balkans, and, in particular, the restructuring of the 
decisionmaking process in the EU, which will be enlarged by the 
EFTA [European Free Trade Association] states, requires a 
Franco-German relationship that is intact. Only when Paris and 
Bonn/Berlin continue to stand trustfully side by side, will it 
be possible to ban the many specters of the past that are 
darting in and out again. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-19393 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu052_h_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-052 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on Iran's Attempt To Stop Trial </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703121794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1103 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DDP/ADN) -- During his testimony to the 
first criminal division of Berlin Regional Court today, Bernd 
Schmidbauer, state minister at the German Chancellery, said that 
an attempt was made to prevent the trial surrounding the attack 
that took place at the Mykonos restaurant. Schmidbauer said 
Iranian Intelligence Minister 'Ali Fallahian had made this 
unreasonable request to him during talks in October 1993. 
Schmidbauer, who is responsible for secret service 
coordination, therefore confirmed the talks with Fallahian, 
which he had previously disputed, on the background to an attack 
on 17 September 1992 during a Socialist International congress, 
in which four exiled Iranian politicians were murdered. 
  During persistent questioning Schmidbauer said he had 
categorically rejected the Iranian's proposal as it was the job 
of independent judges in Berlin to rule on the case. He had 
also said there would be a period of frosty relations between 
the two states if it emerged that Iran was behind the attack. 
The case continues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

