<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industrialists Meet Kohl, Reiterate Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603144794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1338 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Munich (DDP/ADN) -- Hans-Peter Stihl, president of 
the German Association of Chambers of Industry and Commerce, has 
reaffirmed German industry's hope for a continuation of the 
liberal-conservative coalition between the Christian Democratic 
Union, Christian Social Union, and the Free Democrats. A 
red-green government following the Bundestag election in October 
is "not a desirable alternative," Stihl told journalists in 
Munich today. 
  Stihl told the DDP/ADN news agency that industry also 
rejects 
the idea of a social democratic-liberal coalition involving the 
Social Democratic Party [SPD] and the Free Democratic Party, as 
the left wing of the SPD is pursuing a policy hostile toward 
industry and which threatens jobs. His skepticism toward a 
change of government was shared by Klaus Murmann, president of 
the Federal Confederation of German Employers' Associations, 
Tyll Necker of the Federal Association of German Industry, as 
well as Herbert Spaeth of the National Association of German 
Skilled Crafts. 
  The industrialists met with Chancellor Helmut Kohl at the 
"top-level Munich talks of German industry." 

</TEXT>

