<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Under Attack From Within FDP </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603153994 Berlin DIE WELT in German 16 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1603153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Martin S. Lambeck report: "Rexrodt Becoming Target of FDP </F>
Criticism"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- After the lost Lower Saxony elections, 
criticism of Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt is increasing 
within the Free Democratic Party of Germany [FDP]. The party's 
leading circles complain that Rexrodt has not done enough to 
improve the FDP's profile in his department. They say that the 
words that FDP Chairman Klaus Kinkel said after the election 
defeat, "We simply have to get better," were directed at him. 
  The FDP management says: "Rexrodt should finally show that 
he is not only a minister in the federal government, but also an 
FDP politician." The economics minister was criticized by 
Honorary Chairman Hans-Dietrich Genscher, Deputy Chairwoman 
Irmgard Schwaetzer, and former Interior Minister Gerhart Rudolf 
Baum. After all, the economy is a central issue in the 1994 
super election year. Rexrodt has given in to the Christian 
Democratic Union [CDU] in the back room of the coalition too 
often. It has to become obvious that the FDP stands for more 
jobs in the coalition. According to information available to 
DIE WELT, Kinkel personally demanded: "We need a more 
aggressive economic policy." 
  On the FDP's reliability as coalition partner, leadership 
circles say: "We are not a party of people wanting to commit 
political suicide." A shift of the Liberals is practically 
impossible at this point. In Monday's [14 March] management 
meeting, FDP Secretary General Werner Hoyer said: "A coalition 
decision is not a single decision, but a process." 
  What is striking in this context is the restraint shown by 
North Rhine-Westphalian FDP chairman and Kinkel opponent Juergen 
Moellemann. In the 23 May Federal Assembly, Moellemann wants to 
vote for Social Democrat Johannes Rau. Moellemann does not want 
to use the crushing defeat in the Lower Saxony elections against 
Kinkel. The reason: At the Rostock party conference in June, 
Moellemann wants to take the place of Carola von Braun, who 
retired from the presidium. 
  The FDP is concerned about its weak position in the laender 
organizations. The Liberals must be prevented from becoming a 
mere federal party. They say: "The Liberals must not become a 
woman without reproductive organs." 

</TEXT>

