<H3> <TI>   Caen Mayor Backs Down on Kohl Invitation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603135794 Paris AFP in English 1344 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1603135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Paris, March 16 (AFP) -- Caen Mayor Jean-Marie 
Girault on Wednesday [16 March] backed down on a plan to invite 
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl to attend a ceremony there to mark 
the 50th anniversary of D-Day in Normandy on June 6. 
  Girault, who visited the German embassy here, did not hand 
over an invitation to Kohl, but one for ambassador Juergen 
Sudhoff after the two held a meeting, an embassy spokesman said. 
[passage omitted] 
  Speaking on RTL radio later, Girault said he could not 
officially invite Kohl, but still wanted the chancellor to 
attend. He said Sudhoff had accepted the invitation, on 
condition the Bonn government approved it. [passage omitted] 
  An opinion poll in the French Christian weekly LA VIE said 
57 
percent of the French favoured a German Government presence at 
the D-Day ceremonies. 

</TEXT>

