<H3> <TI>   First Taiwanese Frigate Launched in `Utmost Secrecy' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1503130694 Paris LE MONDE in French 15 Mar 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> BR1503130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE MONDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The first of six frigates built by France for Taiwan 
was launched, in utmost secrecy, during the night of 11-12 March 
at Lorient. The launch of the frigate, baptized Mop-1, took 
place at 0300 and was attended only by a Taiwan delegation. 
According to the port authorities, this launch was done at night 
for "technical reasons." 
  In reality, however, the French Government always has been 
reticent about this 14-billion-franc [Fr] naval contract known 
under the codename "Bravo," and it only very reluctantly 
admitted to the existence of a second contract with Taipei for 
60 Mirage 2000-5 fighter aircraft (Fr30 billion). 
  The Mop-1 frigate then was moved to a Lorient-Keroman port 
dock for further arming. 
  The Taiwan vessels will be equipped with French equipment 
and 
arms systems, contrary to what government circles had said at 
the time when the French press disclosed the contract. The 
second vessel, Mop-2, is scheduled to be launched in September. 

</TEXT>

