<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aho, Rehn Differ on Partnership for Peace Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703122194 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1100 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703122194 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In the offer of Partnership for Peace made by the 
North Atlantic Treaty Organization, NATO, Finland is interested 
not only in peacekeeping, but also in participation in 
theoretical and practical training in and planning for search, 
rescue, and humanitarian operations. Tomorrow the government's 
Foreign Affairs Committee will discuss its attitude to 
Partnership for Peace, but will not make any decisions yet. 
Prime Minister Esko Aho, who addressed the Diet's Defense 
Committee, said that the main content of the offer to Finland 
concerns peacekeeping activities. 
  Aho's definition is broader than the stance presented by 
Defense Minister Elisabeth Rehn to the Defense Committee on 
Tuesday [15 March], according to which Finland will limit itself 
to offering peacekeeping training only. 

</TEXT>

