<H3> <TI>   Papandreou Confers With President; New Minister Sworn In </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1603134194 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1603134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Konstandinos Karamanlis and Prime Minister 
Andreas Papandreou met in the presidential palace today and 
discussed developments in The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia [FYROM], the Bosnian crisis, and questions pertaining 
to domestic and foreign policy. 
  Shortly before the meeting at 1230, Athanasios Mikroutsikos 
was sworn in before the president and in the presence of the 
prime minister as the new minister of culture. 
  The president's office issued a statement a short time ago 
noting that at the meeting, the president and the prime minister 
discussed the Yugoslav crisis in particular, reaffirming 
Greece's position that no Balkan country should participate in 
any form of military intervention or in a UN peacekeeping force 
in the former Yugoslavia. They also discussed the latest 
developments in the FYROM issue and prospects uncovered during 
the recent meeting between Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias 
and Cyrus Vance. 
  The statement from the president's office also stressed that 
Karamanlis and Papandreou discussed the Cyprus issue within the 
UN framework and the prospects for Cyprus' accession to the 
European Union. 

</TEXT>

