<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy Calms Fear of Military in Balkans </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1703113194 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 0935 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1703113194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New York, Mar. 17 (A.A.) -- Turkish Ambassador to 
the United Nations Inal Batu said Wednesday [16 March] that 
Turkey has always worked with discipline and faith in any UN 
mission it took part in. 
  Batu quelled fears that Turkish involvement in the Balkans, 
which was Ottoman domain for 500 years, would be a contribution 
toward peace and not conquest [as received]. 
  A meeting is expected to be held in New York between U.N. 
Peace Forces Operations (UNPROFOR) Commander Kofi Hannan [name 
as received] and Batu. 
  Batu is expected to reiterate Turkey's readiness to 
contribute with a mechanized battalion of 1,000 troops, which 
could be deployed within a week. 
  Batu also said that Ankara favors a solution which would 
allow the deployment of Turkish forces in the already secured 
regions in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

