<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Summons French Ambassador </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703093594 Hamburg DPA in German 0832 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703093594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- Francois Scheer, French ambassador to 
Bonn, was summoned to the Foreign Ministry on Thursday [17 
March]. As Foreign Ministry spokesman Michael Gerdts affirmed, 
he will have a discussion with State Secretary Dieter Kastrup. 
  The summons, which in diplomatic jargon usually means the 
presentation of a complaint, is a very unusual event in 
connection with the ambassador of the neighboring country, with 
which relations are very close and friendly. It is obviously 
supposed to express Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel's annoyance 
with Scheer's confidential comments to a small circle of 
journalists on Tuesday. 
  Scheer had regretted the lack of frequency in German-French 
consultations and cautiously implied shock about Germany's tone 
at European Union meetings, also among smaller partners. His 
statements were disseminated without citing him by name. 
  Ambassador Scheer had wanted in any case to discuss with the 
Foreign Ministry preparations for Kinkel's visit to Paris in the 
near future. On Wednesday evening, a Foreign Ministry official 
still emphatically denied that the formal summons was something 
completely unusual between friendly states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

