<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Gives 'Arafat Economic, Political Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603151194 Hamburg DPA in German 1425 GMT 16 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1603151194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis/Bonn (DPA) -- The Federal Government will 
give PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat political and economic support, 
because it considers him to be the guarantor for the 
continuation of the autonomy negotiations with Israel. This 
position of the Federal Government became known in Tunis on 
Tuesday [15 March] on the sidelines of a talk between 'Arafat 
and Juergen Moellemann, president of the German-Arab Society. 
  However, Bonn will not support the efforts of 'Arafat, who 
is 
weakened in his own camp, to get an international armed 
protection force. Bonn will only advocate sending civilian 
observers -- with the participation of the European Union -- to 
the territories occupied by Israel. 
  Bonn sees the Arab-Israeli peace process as being in a 
serious crisis and considers a longer delay likely. It doubts 
that the Israeli withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho will take 
place on 13 April as planned. However, as soon as the autonomy 
administration has been established there, the Federal 
Government wants to open a German coordination office in Jericho. 
  According to information obtained by Bonn, Israel does not 
rule out an attack by Islamic fundamentalists in retaliation for 
the massacre in Hebron. During a meeting with Moellemann on 
Tuesday, Tunisian Foreign Minister Ben Yahya warned against 
"underestimating the explosive potential of Shi'ite 
fundamentalism, in particular in Egypt." 

</TEXT>

