<H3> <TI>   SPD: Election of President Not Signal for Coalitions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603114994 Hamburg DPA in German 0935 GMT 16 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1603114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- According to Federal Manager Guenter 
Verheugen, the Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] does not 
think the result of the presidential election will decide the 
direction of later coalitions in the government. The settlement 
of Richard von Weizsaecker's succession should not be used for a 
change of power, Verheugen said before journalists in Bonn on 
Tuesday evening [15 March]. From the SPD leadership's point of 
view, a signal for the Bundestag election in October is neither 
expected nor desired from the vote of the Federal Assembly. 
  The SPD is interested in preserving "several options" for a 
government formation on the federal level. If the Free 
Democrats do not vote for Christian Democratic Union [CDU] 
candidate Roman Herzog on 23 May, this will not induce the SPD 
to refrain from talks about an alliance after an election 
victory. 
  In the election of the head of state, however, the Free 
Democrats have the opportunity to prove their independence, 
Verheugen said. If liberal political positions are decisive, it 
should not be hard for the Free Democrats to vote for SPD 
candidate Johannes Rau if they compare him with Herzog. 
  According to Verheugen, it is still open when SPD Chairman 
Rudolf Scharping will present his "shadow cabinet." This may be 
done before, after, or at the election party congress in Halle 
in June. The party chairman does not want a debate or private 
talks on that. Scharping is not looking for candidates. This 
is not the right expression. "I would say that he is sorting 
them out," Verheugen said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

