<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   FDP Deputy Urges Support for SPD's Rau </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603115094 Hamburg DPA in German 0953 GMT 16 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1603115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- As a consequence of the election 
defeat in Lower Saxony, Free Democratic Party of Germany [FDP] 
Bundestag Deputy Wolfgang Lueder has called on his party to vote 
for Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] candidate Johannes 
Rau as president in the last ballot in the Federal Assembly on 
23 May. "We should spell with the liberal alphabet in the 
Bundestag election, in order to demonstrate independence," 
Lueder said in an interview with the BERLINER MORGENPOST 
(Wednesday [16 March] edition). Accordingly, the FDP is to vote 
for its candidate Hildegard Hamm-Bruecher -- who is said to have 
no chances -- in the first two ballots, but for Rau in the last 
ballot. 
  In this way, the FDP would also accept that the SPD is today 
the strongest party and that only one SPD presidency (Gustav 
Heinemann) in the FRG's era is "unhealthy" for the SPD, Lueder 
said. North Rhine-Westphalian FDP Chairman Juergen Moellemann 
had also advocated support for Rau. So far, the FDP leadership 
in Bonn has refused to commit itself. 

</TEXT>

