<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   DIHT Calls For Wage Cuts To Combat Unemployment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703112294 Hamburg DPA in German 0922 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The Federation of German Chambers of 
Industry and Commerce [DIHT] has demanded further measures 
against high unemployment from the partners to the wage 
negotiations and the Federal Government. These should include 
low wages for simple work, wage cuts, and changes in social and 
labor market policy. 
  A resolution by the DIHT Executive Committee, entitled 
"Policy for More Employment," which was published in Bonn on 
Thursday [17 March], says: "In order to control the reduction 
of employment, the parties to the wage contracts must also 
facilitate wage cuts, which make it possible to continue 
employment, even in the case of low utilization of production 
capacities." 
  The partners to the wage negotiations should agree on lower 
wages than so far for simple work. They must take into account 
that after reunification, labor "is now available in 
comparatively larger amounts than capital." This is an 
important cause of unemployment, especially in eastern Germany. 
Therefore, east German wages must be adjusted to the west 
German level more slowly than in the past. 
  DIHT calls on the politicians to lower social security 
contributions. Performances by unemployment and pension 
insurance arising from reunification should be financed by the 
state. Active labor market policy must be accessible for more 
unemployed by reducing the expenditure for the individual. 
  Furthermore, DIHT demands that reprivatized companies in 
eastern Germany should be exempt from high severance pay in case 
of lay-offs. They should be treated like newly founded 
companies, which are not obligated to implement social plans 
during the first four years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

