<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Urges EU Promotion of Baltic Sea Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1503161694 Hamburg DPA in German 1511 GMT 15 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1503161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiel (DPA) -- Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, of the 
Free Democratic Party of Germany, wants to submit to the 
European Union [EU] a Baltic Sea promotion program that would 
provide resources for the development of the region. This was 
announced by his state minister, Helmut Schaefer, at the opening 
of the 5th Hanseatic Economic Days of the Baltic Sea countries 
in Kiel on Tuesday [15 March]. With its aid, the European Union 
has contributed to the Baltic Sea countries' development. In 
view of the challenges, such as the integration of the eastern 
Baltic Sea countries into the EU's transport policy, the aid, 
however, is not sufficient in the long run, Schaefer said. 
  The European Union in 1994 must conclude free-trade 
agreements with Poland and the Baltic states. "One of the 
objectives of the German EU Presidency in the next half year 
will be to conclude associate membership agreements with the 
Baltic states as soon as possible, including the prospects for 
future membership," he said. 
  Schleswig-Holstein Minister President Heide Simonis, of the 
Social Democratic Party of Germany, has called for an opening of 
Western markets for the Eastern reformist countries. Despite 
the economic differences, the Baltic Sea region has great market 
opportunities. To utilize these opportunities it is necessary 
to improve the transport infrastructure. This includes the 
construction of the A 20 Baltic Sea highway. Apart from the 10 
Baltic Sea countries, the 5th Hanseatic Economic Days are also 
attended by Great Britain, the Netherlands, Belgium, and France. 

</TEXT>

