<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundesbank Says Exports on `Way to Recovery' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1803072394 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 17 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1803072394 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["kr"-signed report: "Bundesbank: German Export Industry </F>
Is on the Way to Recovery"] 
  [Text] Frankfurt/Main -- The German export industry appears 
to be emerging from the doldrums. That is what the Bundesbank's 
March monthly report maintains in its preamble to an analysis of 
the balance of payments situation, which, with regard to 
long-term capital movements, has registered a record net influx 
of 198 billion German marks [DM] -- four times as much as in 
1992. It reflects expectations surrounding interest rate 
reductions, a more favorable return on the German mark compared 
to U.S. dollar investments, currency speculation considerations, 
as well investments motivated by tax considerations on the part 
of German investors. 
  In the case of trade in goods, despite "a poor situation for 
exports that carried on well into the year," there was an 
improved export surplus of DM59 billion (DM33.7 billion in 
1992), which stemmed from a relatively steep drop in imports. 
The deficit in services fell only slightly to DM36.2 (39.4) 
billion. 
  This was also linked to the decline in registered net 
capital 
yields of DM10 billion, writes the Bundesbank. Because of 
services deficits, German net asset holdings abroad have fallen 
by DM100 billion to DM435 billion over the period from the end 
of 1990 until the middle of 1993. It was also noted that as a 
result of the transfer of domestic savings to foreign capital 
centers prompted by the withholding tax on interest, there was a 
significant increase in capital payments "abroad," which are 
actually attributable to domestic investors. Over the past few 
years, German net capital yield receipts "have been too low by 
several billion German marks." 
  Purchases of securities from abroad rose to a record gross 
sum of DM246 billion. Demand was above all for public authority 
bonds (DM165 billion). At the end of 1993, DM500 billion worth 
of securities issued by public bodies were held abroad, that is, 
almost half of such securities in circulation. 
  German investments abroad totalled DM91 billion gross and 
thus were below last year's level (DM114 billion). The reason 
for the decline was reduced interest on the part of German 
savers in foreign investment certificates: Only DM11 billion 
(DM58 billion in 1992) were invested in such securities. "The 
tax considerations that were to a large extent behind these 
investments appear to have largely come to an end in the early 
part of the summer," stressed the central bank. A "veritable 
sales boom" occurred at the end of the year (taxation of 
half-year profits) resulting in the total of Luxembourg-based 
fund certificates held by Germans between August and the end of 
the year falling by almost a third to DM80 billion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-19512 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu053_h_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-053 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges Communes To Overcome Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703155494 Berlin DIE WELT in German 17 Mar 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> AU1703155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["adh"-signed report: "Bundesbank: Communes Must Master </F>
Crisis Themselves"] 
  [Text] Frankfurt/Main -- The communes must overcome their 
desperate financial situation by themselves. This is the 
conclusion that the Bundesbank has drawn in view of the dramatic 
deficits of the communes, which rose to 10.5 billion German 
marks [DM] in 1993. In the previous year, it was DM9.7 billion, 
in 1990 DM3.6 billion, and in 1989 even a surplus of DM2.2 
billion was produced. The overall debts of the communes stand at 
DM140 billion. 
  In spite of considerable contributions from the "German 
Unity 
Fund," the east German communes produced a deficit of DM7.5 
billion in 1992. The deficit per inhabitant is three times as 
high as in the old laender, especially because of the required 
additional expenditure for infrastructure. 
  Both a stronger rationalization of the administration and 
the 
transfer of communal tasks to private enterprises are required, 
the Bundesbank stressed. It is possible to achieve a balanced 
budget, like in the first half of the 1980's. According to the 
Bundesbank, the strongly differing financial situation of the 
towns in western Germany puts in proper perspective the 
impression that the rise in expenditure that occurred in the 
past few years is a "phenomenon that can hardly be averted" from 
the communes. 
  On the average, personnel costs rose by approximately 8 
percent between 1990 and 1992, which was caused by wage 
increases and the hiring of new personnel. The increase in 
expenditure for material rose approximately 9 percent, and the 
costs for social welfare increased by 12 percent in 1992 alone. 
The receipts of the communes, however, rose by only 6 percent, 
and the transfers from the federal and provincial budgets by 8 
percent. 

</TEXT>

