<F P=100> CANADA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Review Urged, Russian Nationalist `Threat' Cited </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703153894 Montreal Radio Canada International in English 
1430 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703153894 </F>
<F P=104>  Montreal Radio Canada International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Canada's defense minister says the break up of the 
Soviet Union and the end of the Cold War doesn't mean an end to 
all tensions in Europe, and he says Canada must take that fact 
into consideration as it reviews the role of the Canadian 
military in the coming years. 
  David Collenette points to last December's election victory 
by extreme nationalists in Russia as a potential threat to peace 
in the future. Canada's Liberal government has promised deep 
cuts in military spending, but Mr. Collenette says those 
promises were based on the belief that the world had entered a 
more peaceful era and that belief may no longer be valid. 

</TEXT>

