<DOCNO> FBIS3-19543 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu053_n_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-053 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Increased Disarray Seen Among Nonsocialists </TI></H3>
<H4>   * Sasi Makes Appeal </H4>
<F P=102> 94EN0240C Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 20 Feb 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> 94EN0240C </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Finnish Press Agency (FNB) report: "Sasi: Coalition Party </F>
Needs To Debate Issues"] 
  [Text] Kimmo Sasi, vice chairman of the National Coalition 
(Conservative) Party's parliamentary group, is calling for a 
party debate on issues instead of personal matters. It is a 
disturbing sign, according to Sasi, that the new ideas are 
originating outside the party. 
  On Saturday [19 February] Sasi called for an internal party 
debate on values and the future of the kind that has been 
started by the young Finns under the leadership of Dr. Risto E. 
J. Penttila, who in fact also belongs to the Coalition Party. 
  Speaker Riitta Uosukainen (Coalition Party) warned Saturday 
against damaging the working possibilities for "a unified 
Coalition Party that does real work" and demanded that the party 
gather its strength for the election effort next year. 
  A debate on the state of the party has flared up in the 
Coalition Party, and there has been criticism of party chairman 
Pertti Salolainen in particular. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

