<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel, France's Juppe Stress `Unshakeable' Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703155694 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1510 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703155694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel and his French counterpart Alain Juppe have stressed that 
Franco-German friendship is unshakeable and will continue in the 
future to be the "driving force" in European integration. The 
Foreign Ministry has said that, in a telephone conversation 
today, the two ministers resolved to discuss further joint steps 
regarding Kinkel's visit to Paris on 24 March. Reports on 
alleged anxious remarks by French Ambassador Francois Scheer on 
Franco-German relations were devoid of any foundation. 
  Scheer met Dieter Kastrup, state secretary in the Foreign 
Ministry, this morning. According to media reports there was 
annoyance in Bonn about Scheer's remarks. Speaking to foreign 
correspondents in Bonn, Scheer had, among other things, called 
for closer cooperation between France and Germany in the 
expansion of the European Union. 

</TEXT>

