<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papandreou Confident About Policy on FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1703173394 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1600 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1703173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Our policy on the issue of The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] is firmly set out, and will 
produce the expected results, said Prime Minister Andreas 
Papandreou today. The prime minister was replying to 
correspondents' questions as he left the Chamber of Deputies 
where Greece's 150 years of parliamentary life was celebrated. 
  Replying to a question on whether he believes that the many 
open fronts and dangers around us could develop into unfortunate 
situations for our region, Papandreou said he does not think 
anything like this could happen. If we have our eyes open and 
are united with a common goal to protect the nation and our 
people, he said, I think we can overcome all difficulties. 
Responding to another question on whether he feels that some 
are trying to increase the tension in the region with the topic 
of the Turkish troops' participation in Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
Papandreou said: There are always circles who seek division, 
disorientation and promotion of their own interests, but I do 
not think they will succeed in their mission. Replying to 
another question, Papandreou said that our democracy has been 
sheltered long enough to face the problems in our country now. 

</TEXT>

