<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Competitiveness `Will Further Deteriorate' in 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1803150394 Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD in Dutch 18 Mar 
94 p 13 </F>

<F P=103> BR1803150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed S.M.: "Competitive Position Deteriorates </F>
Further"] 
  [Text] Despite the measures taken under the crisis plan, 
the competitiveness of Belgian companies will further 
deteriorate this year. That emerged from calculations by the 
research department of the Kredietbank. In 1994 wages will 
increase in Belgium 0.6 percent quicker than in its five most 
important trading partners, expressed in a single currency. In 
1995 there will be a slight improvement, according to the report. 
  Toward the end of the month the CRB [Central Council for 
Industry] will again issue an opinion on how the competitiveness 
of Belgian companies is developing. The CRB will base itself on 
the figures of the OECD. The Kredietbank has already calculated 
the conclusions which the CRB will reach. 
  From the calculations it appears that company 
competitiveness 
is further deteriorating in 1994, despite wage restraint and 
other measures in the Dehaene government's crisis plan. The 
explanation is simple: Belgium's trading partners are also 
making an effort to keep down wages. In addition, the Belgian 
franc -- after weakening in the fourth quarter of 1993 -- has 
once again increased in value. 
  The result is that Belgium's competitive disadvantage in 
wage 
costs compared to its five major trading partners (Germany, 
France, the Netherlands, United Kingdom and Italy) will increase 
in 1994 from 4.1 percent to 4.9 percent. Compared with 
Belgium's seven biggest trading partners (the five plus the 
United States and Japan). The competitive disadvantage will 
increase from 4.7 percent to 5.3 percent. 
  Assuming that the franc's exchange rate remains stable in 
1994 and 1995, then the competitive disadvantage should decline 
in 1995 to around the 1993 level. 
  The end of the tunnel as regards the restoration of 
Belgium's 
competitive position was not yet in sight, the Kredietbank's 
research department concluded. 
  However, it is possible that the CRB figures will differ 
from 
the Kredietbank's. The discussion between trade unions and 
employers within the CRB concerns the very question of the 
impact of the crisis plan on wage developments in Belgium. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

