<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Adams Claims Government `Blocking' Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803163294 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1525 GMT 18 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1803163294 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Deric Henderson, PRESS ASSOCIATION] </F>
  [Text] The Government is blocking the path to peace in 
Northern Ireland, Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams claimed today. 
Downing Street's attitude was the major obstacle to ending the 
current impasse, he said. The process required flexibility and 
imagination, but the comments of John Major and other Ministers 
suggested those qualities were lacking in Government circles. 
  Mr. Adams said: "Rather than seeking to remove the 
roadblocks on the road to peace, Mr. Major and his collegues 
appear determined to erect more." He welcomed President 
Clinton's "positive and encouraging" attitude in his St. 
Patrick's Day address and the continued interest by the U.S. 
Government in helping the peace process. "This administration 
has clearly shown its willingness to take a fresh approach to 
this conflict and the means by which it can be ended," added Mr. 
Adams. 
  But the Sinn Fein president attacked remarks in the House of 
Commons by Ulster Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew who claimed that 
the Irish Republic's constitutional claim to Northern Ireland 
was an "anachronism." 
  Mr. Adams asked: "What of Britain's claim of sovereignty? Is 
the Government of Ireland Act not an issue? Are we to accept 
that there is no dispute over sovereignty? Has Mr. Mayhew not 
simply dismissed the national aspirations of Irish nationalists? 
How can there be equality if our aspirations are anachronistic?" 

</TEXT>

